          <h2>Lesson 1: Why Glucose Matters</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            Last week you learned the general framework of homeostasis — set points, receptors,
            effectors, and negative feedback. This week we apply that framework to a specific
            system: <strong>blood glucose regulation</strong>. This is arguably the most important
            homeostatic mechanism you will study for AS 91604, because its disruption
            (diabetes) affects millions of people worldwide.
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Slides Reference:</strong> This lesson draws from Peter Shepherd's
              <em>Glucose Homeostasis</em> presentation (University of Auckland). The
              interactive elements below bring the key diagrams and concepts to life.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Glucose as biofuel ── -->
          <h3>Glucose: The Ultimate Biofuel</h3>

          <p>
            Glucose (C₆H₁₂O₆) is a monosaccharide — the primary fuel molecule used by cells
            for aerobic respiration. It is the <strong>predominant carbohydrate</strong> used
            in the body and the starting point for both glycolysis and the Krebs cycle.
          </p>

          <div class="info-cards-row">
            <div class="info-card info-card--brain">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="42" height="42" viewBox="0 0 42 42" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <ellipse cx="21" cy="20" rx="12" ry="10" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.4"/>
                  <path d="M15 20 Q18 14 21 20 Q24 26 27 20" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="2" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="21" y1="30" x2="21" y2="36" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Brain &amp; Nervous System</h4>
              <p>
                The brain relies <strong>almost exclusively</strong> on glucose. Below ~2.5 mmol/L,
                seizures and coma can occur because neurons cannot function without it.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--blood">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="42" height="42" viewBox="0 0 42 42" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <circle cx="21" cy="21" r="10" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none" opacity="0.35"/>
                  <circle cx="21" cy="21" r="5" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1" fill="none" opacity="0.5"/>
                  <ellipse cx="21" cy="21" rx="6" ry="2" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1" fill="none" opacity="0.3"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Red Blood Cells &amp; Immune Cells</h4>
              <p>
                RBCs have no mitochondria — they depend entirely on glucose via anaerobic
                glycolysis. Immune cells also have a high glucose demand during infection.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card info-card--muscle">
              <div class="info-card__icon">
                <svg width="42" height="42" viewBox="0 0 42 42" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M10 26 Q14 14 21 21 Q28 28 32 16" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="2" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="10" y1="26" x2="10" y2="30" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <line x1="32" y1="16" x2="32" y2="12" stroke="var(--green-vivid)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
              <h4>Muscle Cells</h4>
              <p>
                Muscles can use fats and amino acids too, but glucose is the preferred fuel
                during intense activity. Muscle stores glucose as glycogen for quick access.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Too low vs too high ── -->
          <h3>The Danger Zone: Too Low and Too High</h3>

          <p>
            Maintaining blood glucose is literally a matter of <strong>life and death</strong>.
            Both extremes are dangerous, but for different reasons:
          </p>

          <div class="danger-comparison">
            <div class="danger-card danger-card--low">
              <div class="danger-card__header">
                <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M12 3L2 21h20L12 3z" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                  <path d="M12 10v4M12 17v.5" stroke="var(--fluoro-cyan)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
                <h4>Too Low (Hypoglycaemia)</h4>
                <span class="danger-card__threshold">&lt; 3.9 mmol/L</span>
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>Brain cells starve — confusion, seizures, coma</li>
                <li>Symptoms: tremors, sweating, irritability, dizziness</li>
                <li>Adrenaline released as emergency response</li>
                <li><strong>Immediate danger</strong> — can be fatal within hours</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="danger-card danger-card--high">
              <div class="danger-card__header">
                <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
                  <path d="M12 3L2 21h20L12 3z" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" fill="none"/>
                  <path d="M12 10v4M12 17v.5" stroke="var(--fluoro-pink)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                </svg>
                <h4>Too High (Hyperglycaemia)</h4>
                <span class="danger-card__threshold">&gt; 7.0 mmol/L fasting</span>
              </div>
              <ul>
                <li>Glucose binds to proteins (glycation) — damages them</li>
                <li>Above 20 mmol/L: glucose spills into urine, causing water loss</li>
                <li>Long-term damage: retinopathy, nephropathy, neuropathy</li>
                <li><strong>Slow-burn danger</strong> — damage accumulates over years</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="definition-box">
            <div class="definition-box__label">The Set Point</div>
            <p>
              Normal fasting blood glucose is approximately <strong>5 mmol/L</strong>
              (range: 3.9–6.1 mmol/L). This is the value the body "aims for" — the
              homeostatic set point measured after an overnight fast.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── The liver as battery ── -->
          <h3>The Liver: A Rechargeable Glucose Battery</h3>

          <p>
            We can't eat constantly, but the brain needs glucose 24/7. The solution is
            <strong>glycogen storage in the liver</strong>. After a meal, excess glucose is
            converted to glycogen (glycogenesis) and stored. Between meals, glycogen is
            broken back down to glucose (glycogenolysis) and released into the blood.
          </p>

          <div class="battery-diagram">
            <div class="battery-state battery-state--charging">
              <div class="battery-icon">
                <div class="battery-body">
                  <div class="battery-level" id="battery-charge" style="width: 85%"></div>
                </div>
                <div class="battery-tip"></div>
              </div>
              <div class="battery-label">
                <strong>After a meal</strong>
                <span>Insulin stimulates glycogenesis</span>
                <span class="battery-arrow">Glucose → Glycogen</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="battery-state battery-state--discharging">
              <div class="battery-icon">
                <div class="battery-body">
                  <div class="battery-level battery-level--low" style="width: 30%"></div>
                </div>
                <div class="battery-tip"></div>
              </div>
              <div class="battery-label">
                <strong>Between meals</strong>
                <span>Glucagon stimulates glycogenolysis</span>
                <span class="battery-arrow">Glycogen → Glucose</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            The liver stores enough glycogen for <strong>2–3 days</strong>. After that,
            during prolonged starvation, the liver switches to <strong>gluconeogenesis</strong>
            — making new glucose from fats and amino acids. This explains why muscle wasting
            and fat loss occur during starvation.
          </p>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Assessment Tip</h4>
            <p>
              In your report, always explain <em>why</em> glucose regulation matters before
              describing <em>how</em> it works. Linking the mechanism to biological
              consequences (brain function, cell damage) is what lifts your response from
              Achieved to Merit and Excellence.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>


