          <h2>Lesson 2: The Mechanism — Insulin &amp; Glucagon</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            Blood glucose regulation is controlled by two opposing hormones —
            <strong>insulin</strong> (lowers glucose) and <strong>glucagon</strong>
            (raises glucose) — produced by specialised cells in the pancreas. This is
            a textbook example of <strong>antagonistic hormone control</strong>.
          </p>


          <!-- ── Islets of Langerhans ── -->
          <h3>The Islets of Langerhans</h3>

          <p>
            The pancreas sits adjacent to the gut, on the portal vein that drains nutrients
            from the intestine to the liver. Within the pancreas are clusters of endocrine
            cells called the <strong>islets of Langerhans</strong>. Two cell types are critical:
          </p>

          <div class="cell-comparison">
            <div class="cell-card cell-card--beta">
              <div class="cell-card__badge">β-cells</div>
              <h4>Beta Cells</h4>
              <p>
                Detect when blood glucose <strong>rises above ~5 mmol/L</strong>.
                Respond by secreting <strong>insulin</strong> into the bloodstream.
              </p>
              <div class="cell-card__detail">
                <strong>Target tissues:</strong> Liver, muscle, fat cells
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="cell-card cell-card--alpha">
              <div class="cell-card__badge">α-cells</div>
              <h4>Alpha Cells</h4>
              <p>
                Detect when blood glucose <strong>falls below ~5 mmol/L</strong>.
                Respond by secreting <strong>glucagon</strong> into the bloodstream.
              </p>
              <div class="cell-card__detail">
                <strong>Target tissue:</strong> Liver (mainly)
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="connection-box">
            <h4>Why Are Islets So Well Placed?</h4>
            <p>
              The pancreas is positioned on the <strong>portal vein</strong> between the gut
              and the liver. This means islet cells are among the first to detect a rise in
              blood glucose after a meal — and the hormones they release reach the liver
              (the main glucose storage organ) almost immediately.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Hormones ── -->
          <h3>What Is a Hormone?</h3>

          <p>
            Hormones are chemical messengers made in one part of the body that regulate
            processes in another part. Key properties:
          </p>

          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li>Circulate in the bloodstream at <strong>very low concentrations</strong> (picomolar range for insulin) but achieve large effects (millimolar changes in glucose)</li>
            <li>Each hormone has a <strong>specific receptor protein</strong> — insulin only affects cells with insulin receptors (liver, muscle, fat)</li>
            <li>Glucagon receptors are mainly found in the <strong>liver</strong>, so glucagon primarily acts on liver cells</li>
          </ul>


          <!-- ── Insulin action ── -->
          <h3>How Insulin Works: Signal Transduction</h3>

          <p>
            When beta cells detect high glucose, they release pre-packaged insulin from
            vesicles (the insulin was made in advance — gene expression takes too long for
            the rapid response needed). Here's the cascade:
          </p>

          <div class="step-flow">
            <div class="step-flow__item">
              <div class="step-flow__number">1</div>
              <div class="step-flow__content">
                <strong>Insulin binds to receptor</strong>
                <p>Insulin receptor is a transmembrane protein on liver, muscle, and fat cells. Binding causes an <strong>allosteric shape change</strong> in the intracellular domain.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="step-flow__item">
              <div class="step-flow__number">2</div>
              <div class="step-flow__content">
                <strong>Receptor activates intracellular signalling</strong>
                <p>The shape change activates an enzymatic cascade — phosphorylation of proteins inside the cell. The hormone never enters the cell; the signal is <strong>transduced</strong> across the membrane.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="step-flow__item">
              <div class="step-flow__number">3</div>
              <div class="step-flow__content">
                <strong>GLUT4 vesicles move to membrane</strong>
                <p>In muscle and fat cells, the cascade causes vesicles containing GLUT4 glucose transporters to fuse with the plasma membrane. Now glucose can enter the cell.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="step-flow__item">
              <div class="step-flow__number">4</div>
              <div class="step-flow__content">
                <strong>Glucose is stored</strong>
                <p>In liver: glucose → glycogen (glycogenesis via glycogen synthase). In fat cells: glucose → glycerol for triglyceride synthesis. In muscle: glucose used for energy or stored as glycogen.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="step-flow__item">
              <div class="step-flow__number">5</div>
              <div class="step-flow__content">
                <strong>Signal shut-off</strong>
                <p>The insulin receptor is internalised into a vesicle (~1 minute). The vesicle acidifies, changing protein shape so insulin can no longer bind. Insulin is degraded by <strong>insulin-degrading enzyme</strong>. The signal stops — ensuring glucose doesn't drop too far.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Common mistake:</strong> Students often call glucose transporters
              "receptors". GLUT proteins are <strong>transporters</strong> (they move
              glucose across the membrane). The <strong>insulin receptor</strong> is a
              separate protein that detects insulin — don't confuse the two!
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── GLUT4 key point ── -->
          <h3>GLUT4: The Insulin-Dependent Transporter</h3>

          <p>
            Most tissues (brain, liver) have glucose transporters <strong>always present</strong>
            in their membrane — they take up glucose continuously. But muscle and fat cells
            are different: their glucose transporter (GLUT4) is kept <strong>inside the cell
            in vesicles</strong> until insulin signals it to move to the surface.
          </p>

          <div class="key-distinction">
            <div class="key-distinction__item">
              <span class="key-distinction__label">Brain &amp; Liver</span>
              <span class="key-distinction__desc">Glucose transporters always in membrane → constant glucose uptake</span>
            </div>
            <div class="key-distinction__item key-distinction__item--highlight">
              <span class="key-distinction__label">Muscle &amp; Fat</span>
              <span class="key-distinction__desc">GLUT4 in vesicles → only moves to membrane when insulin is present</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p>
            This is why insulin is so important for lowering blood glucose — without it,
            muscle and fat cells <strong>cannot take up glucose</strong>, even if blood
            glucose is dangerously high.
          </p>


          <!-- ── Glucagon ── -->
          <h3>Glucagon: The Opposing Arm</h3>

          <p>
            When blood glucose falls below ~5 mmol/L (e.g. between meals), alpha cells
            secrete <strong>glucagon</strong>. Glucagon binds to receptors on liver cells
            and activates <strong>glycogen phosphorylase</strong>, which breaks down
            glycogen into glucose. This glucose is released into the bloodstream.
          </p>

          <div class="summary-box">
            <h4>The Antagonistic Pair</h4>
            <p>
              <strong>Insulin</strong> (from β-cells) — lowers blood glucose by promoting
              uptake and storage. Activates <strong>glycogen synthase</strong>.<br/>
              <strong>Glucagon</strong> (from α-cells) — raises blood glucose by promoting
              glycogen breakdown. Activates <strong>glycogen phosphorylase</strong>.<br/>
              Together, they form a classic <strong>negative feedback loop</strong>: as
              glucose rises, insulin dominates; as glucose falls, glucagon dominates.
              The variable oscillates around the 5 mmol/L set point.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>


