          <h2>Lesson 3: When It Goes Wrong — Diabetes</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            <strong>Diabetes mellitus</strong> is the primary disease of disrupted glucose
            homeostasis. The name comes from the Greek <em>diabetes</em> (siphon — referring
            to excessive urination) and <em>mellitus</em> (honey — the urine contains
            glucose). There are two main types, and understanding the difference is essential
            for your assessment.
          </p>


          <!-- ── Type 1 vs Type 2 ── -->
          <h3>Type 1 vs Type 2 Diabetes</h3>

          <div class="diabetes-comparison">
            <div class="diabetes-card diabetes-card--type1">
              <div class="diabetes-card__header">
                <h4>Type 1 Diabetes</h4>
                <span class="diabetes-card__tag">No insulin produced</span>
              </div>
              <div class="diabetes-card__body">
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Cause:</strong>
                  <span>Autoimmune destruction of β-cells</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Onset:</strong>
                  <span>Usually young people (~12 years), rapid onset</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Prevalence:</strong>
                  <span>~1 in 300 in New Zealand</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Treatment:</strong>
                  <span>Insulin injections (now genetically engineered)</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Key problem:</strong>
                  <span>Zero insulin → no GLUT4 translocation → muscle/fat can't take up glucose → blood glucose rises unchecked</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="diabetes-card diabetes-card--type2">
              <div class="diabetes-card__header">
                <h4>Type 2 Diabetes</h4>
                <span class="diabetes-card__tag">Insulin resistance</span>
              </div>
              <div class="diabetes-card__body">
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Cause:</strong>
                  <span>Insulin receptors stop responding properly + β-cell decline</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Onset:</strong>
                  <span>Usually older adults, slow onset over years</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Prevalence:</strong>
                  <span>Rising dramatically worldwide — linked to diet and inactivity</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Treatment:</strong>
                  <span>Diet &amp; exercise → drugs (metformin) → insulin injections</span>
                </div>
                <div class="diabetes-card__row">
                  <strong>Key problem:</strong>
                  <span>Insulin present but ineffective → partial glucose uptake → blood glucose still elevated above safe levels</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Complications ── -->
          <h3>Diabetic Complications: Why High Glucose Damages the Body</h3>

          <p>
            High blood glucose causes a process called <strong>glycation</strong> — glucose
            molecules bind directly to proteins in the bloodstream (non-enzymatic, no enzyme
            required). The higher the glucose, the more glycation occurs, and the more damage
            accumulates over time.
          </p>

          <div class="complications-grid">
            <div class="complication-card">
              <h5>Retinopathy</h5>
              <p>Damage to small blood vessels in the retina → blindness</p>
            </div>
            <div class="complication-card">
              <h5>Nephropathy</h5>
              <p>Kidney damage → diabetes is the leading cause of dialysis</p>
            </div>
            <div class="complication-card">
              <h5>Neuropathy</h5>
              <p>Nerve damage, partly from loss of blood supply</p>
            </div>
            <div class="complication-card">
              <h5>Cardiovascular Disease</h5>
              <p>Accelerated atherosclerosis → heart attacks are a major cause of death in diabetics</p>
            </div>
            <div class="complication-card">
              <h5>Peripheral Circulation</h5>
              <p>Poor blood flow to extremities → infections, foot ulcers, gangrene</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="connection-box">
            <h4>HbA1c — Measuring Long-Term Glucose Exposure</h4>
            <p>
              <strong>Glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c)</strong> is the clinical measure of how
              much glucose has been in the blood over time. Since haemoglobin has a half-life
              of ~14 days, HbA1c reflects average blood glucose over 2–4 weeks. If more than
              5% of haemoglobin is glycated, it's concerning. The DCCT trial showed that
              keeping HbA1c low significantly reduces the risk of all diabetic complications.
            </p>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Exercise ── -->
          <h3>Why Exercise Helps: An Alternative GLUT4 Pathway</h3>

          <p>
            There's a powerful insight from the presentation: exercise stimulates GLUT4
            translocation to the membrane <strong>independently of insulin</strong>. Muscle
            contraction uses a different signalling pathway that is <strong>not affected by
            insulin resistance</strong>. This means exercise can lower blood glucose even
            in Type 2 diabetics whose insulin signalling is impaired.
          </p>

          <div class="exam-tip">
            <h4>Excellence-Level Insight</h4>
            <p>
              In your assessment, linking exercise to the GLUT4 pathway as an insulin-independent
              mechanism for glucose uptake demonstrates the kind of biochemical depth that
              characterises an Excellence response. It shows you understand the mechanism, not
              just the outcome.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>


