        <!-- ——————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————
             Check Your Understanding
             —————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— -->
        <section id="check-understanding" class="content-section fade-in-up">
          <h2>Check Your Understanding</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">
            Test your knowledge of glucose homeostasis. Try to answer each question before
            revealing the model answer.
          </p>

          <div class="question-card" id="q1">
            <div class="question-card__badge">Q1 — Achieved</div>
            <p class="question-card__prompt">
              Name the two hormones involved in blood glucose regulation and state where
              each is produced.
            </p>
            <button class="btn btn--secondary reveal-btn" data-target="q1-answer">Reveal Answer</button>
            <div class="question-card__answer" id="q1-answer" hidden>
              <p>
                <strong>Insulin</strong> — produced by <strong>beta (β) cells</strong> in
                the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. Lowers blood glucose.<br/>
                <strong>Glucagon</strong> — produced by <strong>alpha (α) cells</strong> in
                the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. Raises blood glucose.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="question-card" id="q2">
            <div class="question-card__badge">Q2 — Achieved</div>
            <p class="question-card__prompt">
              Explain why glucose is important for the brain and what happens if blood
              glucose falls too low.
            </p>
            <button class="btn btn--secondary reveal-btn" data-target="q2-answer">Reveal Answer</button>
            <div class="question-card__answer" id="q2-answer" hidden>
              <p>
                The brain relies almost exclusively on glucose as its energy source — unlike
                muscle, it cannot easily use fats or amino acids. If blood glucose falls
                below ~2.5 mmol/L (hypoglycaemia), neurons cannot produce enough ATP to
                function, leading to confusion, seizures, and potentially coma or death.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="question-card" id="q3">
            <div class="question-card__badge">Q3 — Merit</div>
            <p class="question-card__prompt">
              Explain how insulin causes glucose to be taken up by muscle cells, using the
              terms: receptor, signal transduction, GLUT4, vesicle.
            </p>
            <button class="btn btn--secondary reveal-btn" data-target="q3-answer">Reveal Answer</button>
            <div class="question-card__answer" id="q3-answer" hidden>
              <p>
                Insulin binds to the <strong>insulin receptor</strong> on the surface of
                muscle cells, causing an allosteric shape change in the intracellular domain.
                This activates a <strong>signal transduction</strong> cascade — a chain of
                phosphorylation reactions inside the cell. The cascade causes <strong>vesicles</strong>
                containing <strong>GLUT4</strong> glucose transporters to move to and fuse
                with the plasma membrane. With GLUT4 now in the membrane, glucose can enter
                the cell down its concentration gradient. Without insulin, GLUT4 stays inside
                the cell and glucose cannot enter.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="question-card" id="q4">
            <div class="question-card__badge">Q4 — Excellence</div>
            <p class="question-card__prompt">
              Compare and contrast Type 1 and Type 2 diabetes in terms of their cause,
              the state of insulin in the body, and why exercise is particularly beneficial
              for Type 2 but not sufficient for Type 1.
            </p>
            <button class="btn btn--secondary reveal-btn" data-target="q4-answer">Reveal Answer</button>
            <div class="question-card__answer" id="q4-answer" hidden>
              <p>
                <strong>Type 1:</strong> Caused by autoimmune destruction of β-cells → no
                insulin is produced. Without insulin, GLUT4 cannot move to the membrane in
                muscle/fat cells, so blood glucose rises unchecked. Exercise alone cannot
                replace insulin because, while exercise does stimulate GLUT4 translocation
                via a separate (insulin-independent) pathway, the glucose-lowering effect is
                temporary and cannot regulate glucose long-term without insulin.<br/><br/>
                <strong>Type 2:</strong> Insulin is still produced but insulin receptors
                become resistant — the signal transduction cascade is impaired. Exercise is
                particularly beneficial because muscle contraction stimulates GLUT4
                translocation through an <strong>insulin-independent pathway</strong> that
                is <em>not</em> affected by insulin resistance. This allows glucose to enter
                muscle cells even when insulin signalling is impaired, directly lowering
                blood glucose. Combined with dietary changes, this can significantly improve
                or even reverse the condition.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>


