          <h2>Lesson 4: Thermoregulation — A Second Homeostatic System</h2>

          <p class="section-intro">
            In Lessons 1–3 you studied glucose homeostasis in detail. Now we look at a second homeostatic system:
            <strong>thermoregulation</strong> — the control of body temperature. The same principles
            apply (set point, negative feedback, receptors, effectors), but the components and mechanisms
            are different. Understanding both systems strengthens your ability to write about homeostasis
            at Level 8 for AS 91604.
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Reading Lesson:</strong> This lesson is information to read and process.
              Work through each section carefully, studying the diagrams and reading the
              simplified explanations. These concepts from Campbell Biology Chapter 40
              are simplified to NZ Curriculum Level 8.
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Section 1: Regulators vs Conformers ── -->
          <h3>Regulators vs Conformers</h3>

          <p>
            Animals manage their internal environment in two fundamentally different ways.
            A <strong>regulator</strong> uses internal mechanisms to control a variable regardless of
            the external environment — for example, a river otter maintains ~37°C body temperature
            whether the water is 5°C or 25°C. A <strong>conformer</strong> allows its internal
            conditions to match the environment — a largemouth bass's body temperature changes with
            the water temperature.
          </p>
          <p>
            The graph below (Fig. 40.7) shows this clearly: the otter's line is flat (regulated),
            while the bass's line follows the ambient temperature (conforming). Humans are thermoregulators
            — we maintain approximately 37°C regardless of external conditions, which requires
            significant energy expenditure.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/regulators-conformers.png`} alt="Figure 40.7: Graph comparing body temperature of a river otter (regulator) and largemouth bass (conformer) across different ambient temperatures" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.7</strong> — The river otter maintains a constant body temperature
              (regulator), while the bass's temperature tracks the environment (conformer).
              Note that an animal can regulate some variables while conforming for others.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 2: Feedback Control ── -->
          <h3>Feedback Control in Homeostasis</h3>

          <p>
            Homeostasis uses <strong>negative feedback</strong> — the same principle you learned for
            glucose regulation. The thermostat analogy (Fig. 40.8) illustrates this perfectly:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>A <strong>sensor</strong> detects a change from the set point (thermometer detects room temperature drop)</li>
            <li>A <strong>control centre</strong> processes the signal (thermostat compares current vs set temperature)</li>
            <li>An <strong>effector</strong> produces a response (heater turns on)</li>
            <li>The response <strong>reduces the stimulus</strong> — this is what makes it "negative" feedback</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            The critical point: the response opposes the change. Temperature too low → heating mechanisms
            activate. Temperature too high → cooling mechanisms activate. The system oscillates around
            the <strong>set point</strong> (~37°C in humans), never perfectly stable but always correcting.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/feedback-thermostat.png`} alt="Figure 40.8: Thermostat negative feedback loop diagram showing how room temperature is maintained at a set point" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.8</strong> — A household thermostat demonstrates negative feedback.
              The heater turns on when temperature drops below the set point and off when it rises above.
              Note also <strong>positive feedback</strong> (bottom of page) — which amplifies a stimulus
              rather than reducing it (e.g. oxytocin during childbirth). Positive feedback is rare in
              homeostasis.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 3: Circadian Rhythms & Acclimatisation ── -->
          <h3>Set Points Are Not Fixed</h3>

          <p>
            The set point for body temperature is not a single fixed number — it fluctuates in a
            <strong>circadian rhythm</strong> (Fig. 40.9). Body temperature is lowest in the early morning
            (~36.7°C) and highest in the late afternoon (~37.3°C). This rhythm is coordinated with
            melatonin secretion and the sleep-wake cycle.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Acclimatisation</strong> is another form of set-point adjustment — a physiological
            change in response to sustained environmental change. Mountain climbers (Fig. 40.10) spend
            time at intermediate altitudes so their circulatory and respiratory systems can adjust to
            lower oxygen levels. This is different from adaptation (which occurs over generations
            through natural selection).
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/circadian-acclimatization.png`} alt="Figure 40.9: Circadian rhythm of body temperature and melatonin, and Figure 40.10: Mountain climbers acclimatising" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Figs. 40.9 &amp; 40.10</strong> — Left: body temperature follows a circadian
              rhythm, peaking in late afternoon. Right: acclimatisation at altitude allows the body
              to adjust its respiratory and circulatory responses to lower oxygen.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 4: Endothermy vs Ectothermy ── -->
          <h3>Endotherms and Ectotherms</h3>

          <p>
            Animals are classified by their primary heat source:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Endotherms</strong> (mammals, birds) — generate heat internally through metabolism.
            They are "warm-blooded" but the more accurate term refers to the heat <em>source</em>,
            not the temperature itself. Endotherms maintain a stable body temperature but at a high
            metabolic cost.</li>
            <li><strong>Ectotherms</strong> (reptiles, amphibians, most fish, invertebrates) — gain most
            of their heat from the external environment. They use less energy on thermoregulation but
            their body temperature varies with the environment.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Note: the terms "cold-blooded" and "warm-blooded" are misleading. A lizard basking in the
            sun can have a higher body temperature than a mammal. The key difference is <em>where the
            heat comes from</em>, not the temperature itself.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/endothermy-ectothermy.png`} alt="Figure 40.11: A walrus (endotherm) and a lizard (ectotherm) showing different thermoregulation strategies" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.11 &amp; Concept 40.3</strong> — Endotherms generate internal
              metabolic heat; ectotherms rely on external heat sources. Both strategies are
              successful — ectotherms dominate in terms of species numbers.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 5: Heat Exchange Mechanisms ── -->
          <h3>Four Mechanisms of Heat Exchange</h3>

          <p>
            All heat exchange between an animal and its environment occurs through four physical
            processes. Understanding these is essential for explaining <em>how</em> thermoregulatory
            responses work:
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Radiation</strong> — emission of electromagnetic waves. A lizard absorbs radiation
            from the sun; all warm objects radiate heat to cooler surroundings</li>
            <li><strong>Evaporation</strong> — liquid water absorbs heat as it converts to gas. This is
            why sweating cools you — the phase change removes heat from the skin</li>
            <li><strong>Convection</strong> — heat transfer by movement of air or liquid past a surface.
            A breeze cools you by carrying away the warm air layer next to your skin</li>
            <li><strong>Conduction</strong> — direct heat transfer between objects in contact. Sitting on
            a cold rock transfers heat from your body to the rock</li>
          </ol>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/heat-exchange.png`} alt="Figure 40.12: Diagram showing radiation, evaporation, convection, and conduction on an iguana" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.12</strong> — The four mechanisms of heat exchange demonstrated on an
              iguana. The <strong>integumentary system</strong> (skin, hair, nails) is the primary
              interface for heat exchange.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 6: Countercurrent Exchange ── -->
          <h3>Countercurrent Heat Exchange</h3>

          <p>
            Many endotherms have a remarkable adaptation in their extremities: <strong>countercurrent
            heat exchange</strong>. Arteries carrying warm blood from the core run alongside veins
            carrying cool blood back from the extremities. Heat transfers from the warmer arterial
            blood to the cooler venous blood along the entire length of the vessels.
          </p>
          <p>
            The result: blood arriving at the extremities (feet, flippers) is already cooled, reducing
            heat loss. Blood returning to the core is pre-warmed, conserving body heat. This is why a
            Canada goose can stand on ice without losing dangerous amounts of heat, and why a dolphin's
            flippers don't drain heat from its core.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/countercurrent-exchange.png`} alt="Figure 40.13: Countercurrent heat exchange in a goose leg and dolphin flipper, showing warm arterial blood transferring heat to cool venous blood" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.13</strong> — Countercurrent heat exchange in a goose leg (left) and
              dolphin flipper (right). Warm arterial blood transfers heat to cooler venous blood
              flowing in the opposite direction, minimising heat loss from extremities.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 7: Cooling, Behavioural, and Metabolic Responses ── -->
          <h3>Cooling Mechanisms and Metabolic Heat</h3>

          <p>
            When body temperature rises above the set point, endotherms activate <strong>cooling
            mechanisms</strong>:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Vasodilation</strong> — blood vessels near the skin surface dilate, increasing
            blood flow to the skin and radiating more heat to the environment</li>
            <li><strong>Sweating</strong> — eccrine sweat glands secrete water onto the skin; evaporation
            removes heat (humans and horses are particularly effective sweaters)</li>
            <li><strong>Panting</strong> — rapid shallow breathing increases evaporative cooling from
            respiratory surfaces (dogs, birds)</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            When body temperature drops, warming mechanisms include <strong>vasoconstriction</strong>
            (reducing blood flow to the skin), <strong>shivering</strong> (involuntary muscle
            contractions producing heat), and activation of <strong>brown adipose tissue</strong>
            (brown fat) — specialised tissue that produces heat through <strong>non-shivering
            thermogenesis</strong>. Brown fat contains many mitochondria and uncouples the electron
            transport chain, producing heat instead of ATP.
          </p>

          <div class="internal-note">
            <svg width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
              <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <path d="M12 8v1M12 12v4" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"/>
            </svg>
            <div>
              <strong>Level 8 note:</strong> Behavioural responses (putting on a jacket, seeking shade)
              are NOT part of the thermoregulatory <em>system</em> and are not valid evidence for
              AS 91604. Only internal physiological mechanisms count. The moderator specifically
              flagged this in MBC's 2022 moderation.
            </div>
          </div>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/evaporative-cooling-brownfat.png`} alt="Behavioural thermoregulation in a dragonfly, evaporative cooling mechanisms, and brown fat PET scan showing metabolically active tissue" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Figs. 40.14–40.16</strong> — Evaporative cooling (sweating, panting), behavioural
              thermoregulation (ectotherms only), and brown fat activity during cold stress (PET scan
              showing metabolically active brown fat around the neck).
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 8: Metabolic Heat Production ── -->
          <h3>Generating Heat: From Pythons to Fever</h3>

          <p>
            Even some ectotherms can generate metabolic heat. Female Burmese pythons (Fig. 40.17)
            raise their body temperature by rhythmic muscle contractions while incubating eggs —
            shivering thermogenesis, just like mammals.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Fever</strong> is an important disruption to thermoregulation. During bacterial
            or viral infection, the hypothalamus raises the set point (e.g. from 37°C to 39°C).
            The body then activates heating mechanisms (shivering, vasoconstriction) to reach this
            new, higher set point. The raised temperature enhances immune function and inhibits
            pathogen reproduction. When the infection clears, the set point returns to normal and
            cooling mechanisms (sweating) activate — this is why fevers "break" with sweating.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/python-inquiry-fever.png`} alt="Figure 40.17: Burmese python inquiry showing oxygen consumption correlating with muscle contractions during egg incubation, and text about fever mechanisms" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.17</strong> — Inquiry: a Burmese python generates heat through muscle
              contractions (shivering) while incubating eggs, as shown by the correlation between
              oxygen consumption and contraction rate.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 9: The Hypothalamus — KEY DIAGRAM ── -->
          <h3>The Hypothalamus: Central Thermostat</h3>

          <p>
            The <strong>hypothalamus</strong> is the control centre for thermoregulation — the
            equivalent of the pancreas in glucose regulation. It contains thermosensitive neurons
            that detect changes in blood temperature, and it also receives input from
            <strong>peripheral thermoreceptors</strong> in the skin (including transient receptor
            potential, or TRP, ion channels).
          </p>
          <p>
            Study this diagram carefully — it shows the complete negative feedback loop for
            thermoregulation in humans:
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure textbook-figure--hero">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/hypothalamus-feedback.png`} alt="Figure 40.18: Complete thermoregulatory feedback loop showing the hypothalamus detecting temperature changes and activating heating or cooling mechanisms" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.18 — KEY DIAGRAM</strong> — The hypothalamic thermostat. When body
              temperature rises: the hypothalamus activates cooling (vasodilation, sweating).
              When body temperature falls: it activates warming (vasoconstriction, shivering).
              Both responses bring temperature back toward the set point of 36–38°C. This is
              the same negative feedback loop structure as glucose regulation — different
              components, same principle.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <div class="key-comparison">
            <h4>Comparing the Two Systems</h4>
            <div class="comparison-grid">
              <div class="comparison-grid__header">Feature</div>
              <div class="comparison-grid__header">Glucose Regulation</div>
              <div class="comparison-grid__header">Thermoregulation</div>

              <div>Set point</div>
              <div>~5 mmol/L blood glucose</div>
              <div>~37°C core temperature</div>

              <div>Sensor/receptor</div>
              <div>Beta &amp; alpha cells in pancreas</div>
              <div>Hypothalamus + peripheral thermoreceptors (TRP channels)</div>

              <div>Control centre</div>
              <div>Pancreas (islets of Langerhans)</div>
              <div>Hypothalamus</div>

              <div>Effectors (too high)</div>
              <div>Liver, muscle, adipose tissue (insulin-driven)</div>
              <div>Sweat glands, skin blood vessels (vasodilation)</div>

              <div>Effectors (too low)</div>
              <div>Liver (glucagon-driven glycogenolysis)</div>
              <div>Skeletal muscle (shivering), skin blood vessels (vasoconstriction), brown fat</div>

              <div>Feedback type</div>
              <div>Negative feedback</div>
              <div>Negative feedback</div>

              <div>Example of breakdown</div>
              <div>Type 1 diabetes (DKA), hypoglycaemic shock</div>
              <div>Hyperthermia (heat stroke), hypothermia</div>
            </div>
          </div>


          <!-- ── Section 10: Bioenergetics ── -->
          <h3>Bioenergetics: Energy and Temperature</h3>

          <p>
            Thermoregulation is energetically expensive. The diagram below (Fig. 40.19) shows
            how animals process energy: food is digested and absorbed, nutrients enter cells for
            cellular respiration, and the ATP produced powers biosynthesis, movement, and
            reproduction. At every step, heat is released as a byproduct — this metabolic heat
            is what endotherms use to maintain body temperature.
          </p>
          <p>
            The total energy used per unit time is the <strong>metabolic rate</strong>. For endotherms
            at rest, this is the <strong>basal metabolic rate (BMR)</strong>. For ectotherms at rest
            at a given temperature, it is the <strong>standard metabolic rate (SMR)</strong>. BMR for
            adult humans is approximately 1,600–1,800 kcal per day for males and 1,300–1,500 kcal for
            females — roughly equivalent to the energy output of a 75-watt light bulb.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/bioenergetics-overview.png`} alt="Figure 40.19: Overview of bioenergetics showing energy flow from food through digestion, cellular respiration, ATP production, and heat release" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.19</strong> — Bioenergetics overview. Note how heat is lost at every
              stage — this "waste" heat is actually what endotherms rely on for thermoregulation.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 11: Metabolic Rate & Body Size ── -->
          <h3>Metabolic Rate and Body Size</h3>

          <p>
            There is a consistent relationship between body size and metabolic rate across all
            animals. Larger animals have higher total metabolic rates (an elephant uses more energy
            than a mouse), but smaller animals have higher <strong>mass-specific metabolic rates</strong>
            (a mouse uses more energy <em>per gram of body mass</em> than an elephant).
          </p>
          <p>
            This has direct consequences for thermoregulation: small endotherms lose heat faster
            (higher surface-area-to-volume ratio) and must eat proportionally more to maintain body
            temperature. A shrew must eat almost constantly; an elephant can go much longer between meals.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/metabolic-rate-body-size.png`} alt="Figure 40.21: Two graphs showing (a) total metabolic rate increasing with body size and (b) mass-specific metabolic rate decreasing with body size" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.21</strong> — (a) Total BMR increases with body mass.
              (b) BMR per kilogram <em>decreases</em> with body mass. Small animals burn more
              energy per gram — they must eat more frequently relative to their size.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 12: Energy Budgets ── -->
          <h3>Energy Budgets</h3>

          <p>
            Different animals allocate their energy differently depending on their thermoregulatory
            strategy, size, and lifestyle. The pie charts below compare three vertebrates: an Ad&eacute;lie
            penguin, a deer mouse, and a ball python.
          </p>
          <p>
            Notice how the endotherms (penguin and mouse) spend a much larger proportion of their
            energy on thermoregulation compared to the ectothermic python. The python spends almost
            nothing on temperature regulation — freeing energy for growth and reproduction. This
            is the trade-off between endothermy and ectothermy.
          </p>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/energy-budgets.png`} alt="Scientific Skills Exercise: Pie charts comparing energy budgets of an Adélie penguin, deer mouse, and ball python across metabolism, reproduction, thermoregulation, activity, and growth" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Energy Budgets</strong> — Compare how each animal allocates its energy.
              Endotherms dedicate significant energy to thermoregulation; the ectothermic python
              allocates almost none, investing more in growth and reproduction.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Section 13: Torpor & Hibernation ── -->
          <h3>Torpor and Hibernation</h3>

          <p>
            When food is scarce or temperatures are extreme, some endotherms reduce their metabolic
            rate dramatically in a state called <strong>torpor</strong>. This saves enormous amounts
            of energy:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Daily torpor</strong> — short periods (hours), seen in hummingbirds and some
            bats. Body temperature drops significantly at night to conserve energy</li>
            <li><strong>Hibernation</strong> — extended torpor (weeks to months) during winter.
            Mammals like ground squirrels can drop their body temperature to near 0°C, with metabolic
            rates 1/20th of normal. They periodically rewarm using brown fat before returning to torpor</li>
            <li><strong>Aestivation</strong> — summer torpor in response to heat and drought, seen in
            some amphibians and reptiles</li>
          </ul>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/hibernation-torpor.png`} alt="Figure 40.22: Circadian clock inquiry during hibernation in European hamsters, and text about torpor, hibernation, and aestivation" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Fig. 40.22</strong> — Inquiry: the circadian clock during hibernation. During deep
              hibernation, the hamster's biological clock stops cycling — an example of how thermoregulatory
              states interact with other physiological rhythms.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>


          <!-- ── Summary Box ── -->
          <h3>Concept Summary</h3>

          <figure class="textbook-figure">
            <img src={`${base}/images/thermo/concept-summary.png`} alt="Concept 40.3 summary: key points about thermoregulation including endothermy, ectothermy, heat exchange, insulation, countercurrent exchange, and hypothalamic control" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption>
              <strong>Concept 40.3 Summary</strong> — Review this summary box. Make sure you can
              explain each bullet point using biological terminology at Level 8 depth.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

